            <fr:title text="Convergent Sequence">Convergent Sequence</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>A sequence is converges to a real number <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> if, for any number <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\epsilon  < 0]]></fr:tex>, there exists and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N\in  \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> such that for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\geq  N]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|a_n-a|<\epsilon ]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
            <html:p>We can also define the convergence of a sequence using topology. First, we define the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\epsilon ]]></fr:tex>-neighborhood of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex>,
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[V_\epsilon (a)=\{x\in \mathbb {R}:|x-a|<\epsilon \}]]></fr:tex></html:p>
            <html:p>The <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\epsilon ]]></fr:tex>-neighborhood of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is all points with a distance from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> less than <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\epsilon ]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
            <html:p>A sequence converges to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> if for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\epsilon ]]></fr:tex>-neighborhood of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex>, there exists a point in the sequence after which all terms are in the neighborhood.</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>23</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:title text="Convergent Sequences are Bounded">Convergent Sequences are Bounded</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>A bounded sequence is a sequence where there exists a number <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M>0]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|x_n|\leq  M]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in  \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
                <html:p>Every <fr:link href="/forest/001F/" title="Convergent Sequence" uri="https://andrewczezowski.github.io/forest/001F/" display-uri="001F" type="local">convergent sequence</fr:link> is bounded.</html:p>
                <html:p>The proof of this statement is outlined as follows. Firstly, since the sequence is convergent we know that we have a limit (<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[l]]></fr:tex>). So, we can consider for instance an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\epsilon  = 1]]></fr:tex> and an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N]]></fr:tex> such that for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\geq  N]]></fr:tex> we have 
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[|x_n|<|l|+1]]></fr:tex>
Now we simply need to choose an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> which is the maximum of the set of the finite elements before <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|x_n|<|l|+1]]></fr:tex>. From this we recover the statement for the definition of a bounded sequence.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
